# Android Compose Project Rules

## General

* Use Kotlin only
* Use Jetpack Compose with Material3
* Follow MVVM architecture
* Use StateFlow for UI state
* Avoid LiveData unless explicitly requested
* Keep composables stateless whenever possible
* Separate UI logic from business logic
* Keep files small and modular

---

## UI Rules

* Use Material3 components
* Support dark mode
* Avoid hardcoded colors
* Use MaterialTheme.colorScheme
* Use Modifier.fillMaxWidth() instead of fixed widths when possible
* Keep composables reusable
* Prefer simple layouts over deeply nested layouts

---

## Compose Rules

* Avoid putting business logic inside composables
* Use remember only for UI state
* Use collectAsState() for StateFlow
* Use immutable UI state data classes
* Keep recomposition efficient
* Avoid unnecessary LaunchedEffect usage

---

## ViewModel Rules

* All screen state should come from ViewModel
* Use MutableStateFlow internally
* Expose StateFlow externally
* Do not expose mutable state to UI
* Handle validation inside ViewModel

---

## Navigation Rules

* Use Navigation Compose
* Keep routes centralized
* Avoid passing large objects through navigation
* Use IDs instead of serialized objects

---

## Room Rules

* Use Room for local persistence
* Use suspend functions in DAO
* Keep database operations outside composables
* Repository handles data source coordination

---

## Code Style

* Use clear naming
* Avoid overly abstract architecture
* Prefer readability over cleverness
* Keep beginner-friendly structure
* Add comments only when necessary

---

## Project Goal

This project is a portfolio-ready modern Android application focused on:

* Jetpack Compose
* MVVM
* StateFlow
* Room
* Material3
* Clean and maintainable architecture

Avoid overengineering.
Prioritize simplicity, readability, and production-like structure.
